06734nam a22009015i 9781487574710DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191995onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875747107 a10.3138/97814875747102doi  a(DE-B1597)536831  a(OCoLC)1090920188  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aLA417b.B49 1995eb 7aEDU0150002bisacsh04a370.19/3422000aBeyond Political Correctness :bToward the inclusive university /ced. by Stephen Richer, Lorna Weir. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tIntroduction: Political Correctness and the Inclusive University -- tPART ONE. PC: The Social Organization of a Right-Wing Offensive -- t'Politically Correct': An Ideological Code -- tPC Then and Now: Resignifying Political Correctness -- tFraming the 'Western Tradition' in Canadian PC Debates -- tAcademic Freedom Is the Inclusive University -- t'Fit and Qualified': The Equity Debate at the University of Alberta -- tPART TWO. Creating Inclusive Pedagogy in Practice -- tDiversity, Power, and Voice: The Antinomies of Progressive Education -- tReaching the Men: Inclusion and Exclusion in Feminist Teaching -- tRe: Turning the Gaze -- tUnderstanding and Solidarity -- tJoining the Dialogue -- tAnti-Racist Education and Practice in the Public School System0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe term ‘political correctness’ has lately been transformed into a weapon of neo-conservatism. Once used to poke fun at social movements and civil-rights group for occasional lapses into rigidity, it has since become a popular handle for the neoconservative critique of higher education. Aimed at anti-racist and anti-sexist initiatives within universities, colleges, and other major social institutions, the term is used to discredit such innovations as employment equity, selective recruitment of students from groups that have suffered systemic discrimination, sexual harassment policies, and women’s studies programs, casting these as forms of tyranny that destroy academic freedom and merit. This anthology is the first sociological analysis of political correctness and the first study of the phenomenon in Canada. Contributors argue on behalf of an inclusive university, showing that recent reforms not only work toward broadening human rights but provide a welcome reorganization of knowledge. All but two papers have been written specifically for this text. Part One explores the history and social organization of the discourse, with the accent on Canadian material. The essays explore what the term has signified to different groups and to what ends they have used it. This section moves from an overview of political-correctness discourse to its explicit manifestation within universities in debates concerning academic ideals. Part Two looks at the classroom, a major site for building the inclusive university. Here, contributors explore feminist and anti-racist teaching and the limitations to such teaching imposed by the economic and political contexts of contemporary universities. As these scholars trenchantly reveal, the political-correctness debate will ultimately affect the lives of everyone. This book offers insight into the values, ideals, and motives of both sides.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEducation, HigherxAims and objectiveszCanada. 0aEducation, HigherxPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aEducational equalizationzCanada. 0aMulticultural educationzCanada. 0aPolitical correctnesszCanada. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh1 aBankier, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id